Vaccination of fish has become very important in aquaculture. Originally, it was thought that this could be done by immersion of fish in a tank with vaccine. However, this required large concentrations of vaccine, which made this method prohibitively expensive. Moreover, protective immunity was not uniformly achieved by this method. Currently, vaccination is done by intraperitoneal injection in almost all instances (Rødseth and Moen, personal communication). Fish are placed briefly in an anesthetic solution before being injected manually (Figures 4(a) and (b)
). The Norwegian company Skala Maskon has developed a machine that can vaccinate 20 000 salmon h−1 and separate the fish into different weight classes while rejecting malformed fish (Figure 5
). In some countries oral vaccination is used by encapsulating the vaccine in different components (reviewed by Gomez-Casado et al., 2011).
